#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.10.2 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:5
msgid ""
"This release deals with a number of bugs that turned up in 1.10.1 and adds "
"various build and release improvements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:8
msgid "Numpy 1.10.1 supports Python 2.6 - 2.7 and 3.2 - 3.5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:12
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:15
msgid "Relaxed stride checking is no longer the default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:16
msgid ""
"There were back compatibility problems involving views changing the dtype of "
"multidimensional Fortran arrays that need to be dealt with over a longer "
"timeframe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:21
msgid "Fix swig bug in ``numpy.i``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:22
msgid ""
"Relaxed stride checking revealed a bug in ``array_is_fortran(a)``, that was "
"using PyArray_ISFORTRAN to check for Fortran contiguity instead of "
"PyArray_IS_F_CONTIGUOUS. You may want to regenerate swigged files using the "
"updated numpy.i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:28
msgid "Deprecate views changing dimensions in fortran order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:29
msgid ""
"This deprecates assignment of a new descriptor to the dtype attribute of a "
"non-C-contiguous array if it result in changing the shape. This effectively "
"bars viewing a multidimensional Fortran array using a dtype that changes the "
"element size along the first axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.10.2-notes.rst:34
msgid ""
"The reason for the deprecation is that, when relaxed strides checking is "
"enabled, arrays that are both C and Fortran contiguous are always treated as "
"C contiguous which breaks some code that depended the two being mutually "
"exclusive for non-scalar arrays of ndim > 1. This deprecation prepares the "
"way to always enable relaxed stride checking."
msgstr ""

